<P>The&s;e beginnings of years happen a day and a half before the middle Equi|noxes of the Spring, according to <HI>Ptolomy;</HI> and five days and a half before the &s;ame Equinoxes, according to the moderns: wherefore they may be taken for a kind of middle Equinoxes of the <HI>Indians.</HI> The fir&s;t new Moon after the be|ginnings of the&s;e &s;olar Synodical years, mu&s;t be the fifth of the Civil year when the Intercalation precedes the&s;e beginnings, as it happen'd in the year 1685 and 1688; and it mu&s;t be the &s;ixth of the Civil year in the other years.</P>
<P>The&s;e are the fir&s;t new Moons &s;ince the Equinoxes of this &s;ort, calculated for the preceding years.</P>
